<subSubSection id="1EA273C55712FFAC55E8FE97FC12DEA7" pageId="7" pageNumber="339" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5607204E5712FFAC55E8FE97FC12DEA7" blockId="7.[151,1436,223,646]" pageId="7" pageNumber="339">
<emphasis id="64CCFC5C5712FFAC55E8FE97FEBBDDAB" bold="true" box="[199,315,367,393]" pageId="7" pageNumber="339">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species has been found only twice, originally in the 
<collectingCountry id="2EAF60DE5712FFAC569DFE97FC68DDAB" box="[946,1000,367,393]" name="United States of America" pageId="7" pageNumber="339">USA</collectingCountry>
and then in 
<collectingCountry id="2EAF60DE5712FFAC5141FE97FB2BDDAB" box="[1134,1195,367,393]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="339">India</collectingCountry>
. The original description (
<bibRefCitation id="32295DBF5712FFAC55FCFE6BFEFCDD8C" author="Brunson, R. B." box="[211,380,403,430]" pageId="7" pageNumber="339" pagination="325 - 352" refId="ref11582" refString="Brunson, R. B. (1950) An introduction to the taxonomy of the Gastrotricha with a study of eighteen species from Michigan. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 69, 325 - 352. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3223127" type="journal article" year="1950">Brunson, 1950</bibRefCitation>
) is scanty and not additional information was provided by 
<bibRefCitation id="32295DBF5712FFAC510EFE6CFA9BDD8F" author="Rao, R. K. &amp; Mohan, P. C." box="[1057,1307,403,430]" pageId="7" pageNumber="339" pagination="146 - 153" refId="ref13428" refString="Rao, R. K. &amp; Mohan, P. C. (1987) Gastrotrich fauna of India with notes on their distribution. Uttar Pradesh Journal of Zoology, 7, 146 - 153." type="journal article" year="1987">Rao &amp; Mohan (1987)</bibRefCitation>
. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="32295DBF5712FFAC559AFE40FEE8DDF0" author="Brunson, R. B." box="[181,360,439,466]" pageId="7" pageNumber="339" pagination="325 - 352" refId="ref11582" refString="Brunson, R. B. (1950) An introduction to the taxonomy of the Gastrotricha with a study of eighteen species from Michigan. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 69, 325 - 352. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3223127" type="journal article" year="1950">Brunson (1950)</bibRefCitation>
, the body appears to be scaled but distinct scales were not observed; moreover, the only spines present, numbering 5, appear arranged in a transverse row across the dorsal anterior region of the trunk according to the drawing (
<bibRefCitation id="32295DBF5712FFAC5404FE07FE55DE38" author="Brunson, R. B." box="[299,469,511,538]" pageId="7" pageNumber="339" pagination="325 - 352" refId="ref11582" refString="Brunson, R. B. (1950) An introduction to the taxonomy of the Gastrotricha with a study of eighteen species from Michigan. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 69, 325 - 352. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3223127" type="journal article" year="1950">Brunson, 1950</bibRefCitation>
, Fig. 46, page 347). Indeed, all these characters combinations would make the species unique; however, a redescription of the taxon based on living specimens from the 
<emphasis id="64CCFC5C5712FFAC516FFDDCFB44DE1F" box="[1088,1220,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="339">terra typica</emphasis>
is much needed to allow morphological identification with some degree of confidence. In the meantime, records of the species from distant geographic areas (e.g., 
<collectingCountry id="2EAF60DE5712FFAC54C2FD93FDA8DEA4" box="[493,552,619,646]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="339">India</collectingCountry>
) should be considered tentative.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
